post_cb({"26081738": {"ParentId": "26081712", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>This is specified in the C++ Standard (Draft Standard N3337)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_26081712_26081738_0\"><strong>4.9 Floating-integral conversions</strong></p>\n<p id=\"so_26081712_26081738_1\">1 A prvalue of a floating point type can be converted to a prvalue of an integer type. The conversion truncates; that is, the fractional part is discarded. The behavior is undefined if the truncated value cannot be represented in the destination type. [ <em>Note</em>: If the destination type is bool, see 4.12. \u2014 <em>end note</em> ]</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "434551", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "26081738", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-09-28T04:50:15.300", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-28T04:50:15.300"}, "26081736": {"ParentId": "26081712", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>C++11 \u00a74.9/1:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_26081712_26081736_0\"><strong>\u201d</strong> The conversion truncates; that is, the fractional part is discarded. The behavior is undefined if the truncated value cannot be\n  represented in the destination type.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That\u2019s it, the theory of it: <em>because the standard says so</em>.</p>\n<p>It's a reasonable language design choice but by no means the only possible reasonable choice.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "464581", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "26081736", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2014-09-28T04:50:04.223", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-28T04:50:04.223"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_26081712_26081736_0": {"section_id": 37, "quality": 0.8666666666666667, "length": 13}, "so_26081712_26081738_1": {"section_id": 37, "quality": 0.8125, "length": 26}}, "n3337": {"so_26081712_26081736_0": {"section_id": 34, "quality": 0.8666666666666667, "length": 13}, "so_26081712_26081738_1": {"section_id": 34, "quality": 0.8125, "length": 26}}, "n4659": {"so_26081712_26081736_0": {"section_id": 37, "quality": 0.8666666666666667, "length": 13}, "so_26081712_26081738_1": {"section_id": 37, "quality": 0.75, "length": 24}}}, "26081712": {"CommentCount": "1", "ViewCount": "60", "CreationDate": "2014-09-28T04:44:52.683", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-28T04:50:15.300", "Title": "About float to int", "AcceptedAnswerId": "26081738", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "26081712", "Score": "1", "Body": "<pre><code>float x = 2.5;\nint i = (int)x;\n</code></pre>\n<p>We all know the result is 2, but I want to know why we get this result, what is the theory and how the system work? Can it be explained using binary form (IEEE)?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++>", "OwnerUserId": "4072811", "AnswerCount": "2"}});